The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package. It provides an `IFileSystem` interface that wraps `File`, `Directory`, etc.

**Steps:**

1. `dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions`
2. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling static `File`/`Directory` methods directly:
   ```csharp
   public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
   {
       public string Load(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);
       public void Save(string path, string content) => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);
       public bool DirExists(string path) => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
   }
   ```
3. In production, register `FileSystem` (the real implementation):
   ```csharp
   services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
   ```
4. In tests, use `MockFileSystem` (included in `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`):
   ```csharp
   var fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
   {
       { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{ }") }
   });
   var svc = new MyService(fs);
   Assert.True(fs.Directory.Exists("/data"));
   ```

This avoids touching the real file system in tests and keeps your code easily mockable with no custom abstractions to maintain.
